columns.expression: Sales[Quantity] * CALCULATE(MAXX('Product', Product[Unit Price]), FILTER('Product', Product[Productkey] = Sales[ProductKey]))

measures.name: Total Sales%
measures.description:
/TOTALYTD(SUM([Sales Amount]),'Date'[Datekey])

This calculation is used to find the year over year growth of a sales amount. The calculation divides the current sales amount by the cumulative sales amount up until the same date of the previous year. The result is the percent

measures.name: Sales Amount
measures.description: This calculation computes the total revenue of sales by summing up the revenue earned from each sale. This is done by multiplying the quantity for each sale by the unit price for that sale and then summing up the result of those multiplications for all of the sales.

measures.name: Discount
measures.description: This calculation sums up the total discounts given on all sales items by multiplying the quantity of each item with its unit discount.

measures.name: Discount%
measures.description: The calculation is used to determine the discount amount as a percent of total sales amount. For example, if a business had sales amount of $100, and a discount of $10, the calculation would be 10/100, which is 10% discount.

measures.name: Max Discount %
measures.description: This calculation calculates the maximum discount percentage for sales on products with a specific color. Specifically, it uses the Sales table to find the highest discount percentage for each product, and then further filters it to narrow down to only products with the specific color that is given.

measures.name: Max of Sales Amount
measures.description: This calculation looks at the Sales table and returns the maximum sales (MaxX) value found when taking the quantity multiplied by the unit price for each sales item. In other words, it gets the highest sale value from a given set of sales data.

measures.name: Max of Discount
measures.description: The calculation takes the maximum sales figure multiplied by the unit discount across all sales records. Effectively, it is finding the most profitable combination of sale quantity and the associated unit discount.

measures.name: NetPrice
measures.description: The SUM((Sales[Net Price])) calculation is adding together the total value of all net sales in a given aggregate, such as a company's total sales for a given period. This calculation is useful for understanding the overall performance of a business.

measures.name: Quantity sold
measures.description: This calculation example totals the quantity sold across all sales records in a given data set. This would allow a business to quickly view the total quantity sold of a certain item across all sales.

measures.name: Sales YTD
measures.description: This calculation calculates the total sales for the current calendar year by summing the total sales for each Sales record within the Sales table, filtered to include only records with Orderdates for the days in the current calendar year.

measures.name: Total Numbers of orders
measures.description: This calculation is counting the number of order dates in a Sales table. This calculation is useful to understand how many orders were made during a certain period of time.

measures.name: Total Sales for HA and Computers
measures.expression: CALCULATE(SUMX(FILTER(Sales, OR(RELATED('Product Category'[Category])="Home Appliances",RELATED('Product Category'[Category])="Computers")), Sales[Unit Price]*Sales[Quantity]), ALL(Sales))
measures.description: This calculation calculates the total sale amount of Home Appliances and Computers of all transactions in the Sales table. It does this by summing the product of the Unit Price and Quantity fields of each sale belonging to either Home Appliances or Computers Product Categories in the Sales table. The ALL(Sales) part

measures.name: Total Sales for Selected Color
measures.description: This calculation takes records from the Sales table and multiplies each Quantity by the Unit Price to get the total sum of sales for items of the color Black that appear in the Product table.

measures.name: YoY% Sales
measures.expression: DIVIDE (SUM ( Sales[Sales Amount Column] )- CALCULATE (SUM ( Sales[Sales Amount Column] ),PARALLELPERIOD ( _Date[Date], -1, YEAR )),CALCULATE (SUM ( Sales[Sales Amount Column] ),PARALLELPERIOD ( _Date[Date], -1, YEAR )))
measures.description: This calculation is used to calculate the year-over-year growth rate in sales amounts. It divides the difference between the total sales amount this year and the total sales amount from one year ago by the total sales amount from one year ago.
